pioid receptor agonist with NMDA antagonist properties","Selective kappa-opioid receptor agonist","Mixed agonist-antagonist at opioid receptors"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMethadone functions as a \u003Cstrong\u003Efull mu-opioid receptor agonist with NMDA antagonist properties\u003C/strong\u003E. This dual mechanism contributes to its clinical utility. The long elimination half-life (15-60 hours) makes it particularly useful for once-daily dosing in opioid replacement programmes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompetitive antagonist at mu-opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes drugs like naloxone, which block rather than activate opioid receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial agonist at mu-opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes drugs like buprenorphine, which produce a ceiling effect\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective kappa-opioid receptor agonist\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as methadone primarily acts at mu-opioid receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed agonist-antagonist at opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes drugs like pentazocine, not methadone\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptor antagonist activity may help limit tolerance development and enhance analgesic efficacy in chronic pain conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Methadone acts as both a full mu-opioid receptor agonist and NMDA receptor antagonist.","The long elimination half-life of methadone (15-60 hours) enables once-daily dosing in opioid replacement therapy.","NMDA receptor antagonism may reduce opioid tolerance development and enhance pain control."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53774"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17030"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53774"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T16:03:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T16:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9720"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68317"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous 